Respect the fish and chips
a little bit more, right?

03:40.565 --> 03:41.835
Respect the fish and chips, man.

03:48.020 --> 03:49.608
For over 500 years,

03:49.643 --> 03:52.266
the icy waters
off Newfoundland's coast

03:52.301 --> 03:56.063
overflowed with a seemingly
endless bounty of cod.

03:56.097 --> 03:58.168
Fishermen from all over...

03:58.203 --> 04:01.586
As far away as England,
Portugal, and Spain...

04:01.620 --> 04:04.382
Came here
to pull them from the sea.

04:04.416 --> 04:06.418
They built entire food cultures

04:06.453 --> 04:08.765
around the delicate,
white-fleshed fish.

04:08.800 --> 04:12.942
And for most of its history,
cod defined the culture here.

04:12.976 --> 04:15.358
Cod was king.

04:17.878 --> 04:21.571
Ottawa is about to announce
a moratorium on northern cod.

04:21.606 --> 04:24.402
Small independents,
big company trawlers,

04:24.436 --> 04:26.196
all will have to pull their nets

04:26.231 --> 04:27.853
and dock their boats.

04:27.888 --> 04:32.030
But in 1992,
after years of overfishing,

04:32.064 --> 04:34.964
the Canadian government
shut the industry down.

04:34.998 --> 04:36.966
Six generations down the line,
passed down,

04:37.000 --> 04:39.589
and he's done nothing but...

04:39.624 --> 04:41.591
The moratorium wiped out

04:41.626 --> 04:43.938
the main source of income
for the province

04:43.973 --> 04:45.423
and ended a way of life.

04:45.457 --> 04:47.287
And though
it's been loosened some,

04:47.321 --> 04:49.979
the moratorium
is still in effect today.

04:50.013 --> 04:53.154
What was the spirit
of the people in '92?

04:53.189 --> 04:55.295
Think about it; think about
your number one industry.

04:55.329 --> 04:56.365
No one could fish.

04:56.399 --> 04:57.883
- Culture...
- Nothing, zero.

04:57.918 --> 05:00.438
It went from going out
to jig a fish with your family

05:00.472 --> 05:01.439
or whenever you wanted

05:01.473 --> 05:03.061
to absolutely nothing.

05:03.095 --> 05:05.374
So it just, like, tore the heart
and soul out of people.

05:05.408 --> 05:07.445
What did people change cod for?

05:07.479 --> 05:09.964
Tilapia?

05:09.999 --> 05:11.725
Can I ask this, though?

05:11.759 --> 05:14.348
Was it warranted,
the closing down of the fishery?

05:14.383 --> 05:16.005
- Yeah.
- It was.

05:16.039 --> 05:18.041
Thing was, I mean, a lot of
the in-shore small guys

05:18.076 --> 05:19.457
were talking about it for years,

05:19.491 --> 05:20.830
talking about,
"We can't keep this up."

05:20.837 --> 05:22.349
Like, the factory trawlers
and the fisheries

05:22.356 --> 05:23.737
were just getting bigger
and bigger,

05:23.771 --> 05:27.672
and it's like, how do you put
a factory trawler

05:27.706 --> 05:30.088
that's just dragging the seas...

05:30.122 --> 05:31.400
Everything in the ocean.

05:31.434 --> 05:34.092
From multiple countries,
including our own,

05:34.126 --> 05:36.577
for years and years
and not have an effect?

05:36.612 --> 05:38.510
It was very dark times.

05:38.545 --> 05:39.649
- But better now.
- Yes.

05:39.684 --> 05:40.685
- Getting better.
- Yeah.

05:40.719 --> 05:42.342
From what we've seen...

05:42.376 --> 05:44.198
And I've talked to fishermen
in the bays and stuff...

05:44.205 --> 05:45.586
Cod's coming back.

05:45.621 --> 05:47.208
- Cod is king still.
- Cod is still king.

