09:17.177 --> 09:19.938
Homemade fries,
always a good thing.

09:19.973 --> 09:23.977
How Canadian is Newfoundland?

09:24.011 --> 09:26.635
You know, we have this
kind of complex relationship

09:26.669 --> 09:28.775
here in Newfoundland
with the rest of Canada.

09:28.809 --> 09:32.882
You know, we're a very old
British colony here,

09:32.917 --> 09:35.402
but we've only really been
part of Canada since 1949.

09:35.436 --> 09:38.578
And I think for a long time,
on the mainland of Canada,

09:38.612 --> 09:41.960
there was kind of this
stereotype of Newfoundlanders

09:41.995 --> 09:44.342
as being, you know,
poor and uneducated,

09:44.376 --> 09:46.793
kind of that goofy Newfy
stereotype kind of stuff

09:46.827 --> 09:48.070
that happened.

09:48.104 --> 09:50.624
And over the past 10, 20 years,

09:50.659 --> 09:52.143
there's been a real shift

09:52.177 --> 09:55.180
in how the rest of Canada
perceives Newfoundland

09:55.215 --> 09:56.630
but I think also

09:56.665 --> 09:58.736
as how Newfoundlanders
perceive themselves.

09:58.770 --> 10:00.282
And people, I think,
are starting to say,

10:00.289 --> 10:02.774
"Hey, we don't have
to just import food

10:02.809 --> 10:05.018
from, you know,
the United States or Canada."

10:05.052 --> 10:06.606
You know, the stuff
that we have here,

10:06.640 --> 10:08.262
the ingredients
that we have here

10:08.297 --> 10:09.850
are actually pretty special.

10:09.885 --> 10:12.542
You could actually shoot a bird

10:12.577 --> 10:14.268
and serve it in a restaurant.

10:14.303 --> 10:16.305
If you do that in Montreal,
you get arrested.

10:16.339 --> 10:18.514
You can shoot rabbits
and serve them in restaurants.

10:18.548 --> 10:20.129
Yeah, we have the benefit
of that here, yeah.

10:20.136 --> 10:23.277
This is an enormous
and unique advantage.

10:23.312 --> 10:27.178
