Whoa, whoa.
Wait a minute.

14:42.605 --> 14:43.883
This is your first time...

14:43.917 --> 14:45.401
Our first time in Newfoundland.

14:45.436 --> 14:47.196
We've tried to come
on a couple of occasions,

14:47.231 --> 14:48.715
but no, we've never been here.

14:48.749 --> 14:51.200
Proud Canadians.

14:51.235 --> 14:53.306
This is not
one of the destinations

14:53.340 --> 14:56.309
that a Canadian ends up in.

14:56.343 --> 14:59.208
And yet you decided to open
a fine-dining restaurant

14:59.243 --> 15:01.314
that, by definition, is seasonal

15:01.348 --> 15:04.800
and requires at least
a significant part

15:04.834 --> 15:06.284
of your clientele
to get on a plane

15:06.319 --> 15:09.046
and make the kind of commitment
that these

15:09.080 --> 15:10.944
clearly have not made.

15:10.979 --> 15:12.463
And this is them!

15:12.497 --> 15:15.604
Yeah, I mean, we just plan
to do what we love to do

15:15.638 --> 15:18.641
and cook good food and
celebrate Newfoundland product.

15:18.676 --> 15:20.747
And where do these oysters
hail from?

15:20.781 --> 15:23.508
- These are Beau Soleil oysters.
- Beau Soleil, yeah.

15:23.543 --> 15:28.065
Named after the early
Manson family killer?

15:28.099 --> 15:29.611
Was there a Beausoleil
in the Manson family?

15:29.618 --> 15:30.964
Bobby Beausoleil.

15:30.999 --> 15:32.759
In fact, the entire
Manson family's killings

15:32.793 --> 15:34.547
were designed to draw suspicion
away from Bobby Beausoleil.

15:34.554 --> 15:36.763
I was always a fan
of Squeaky Fromme.

15:36.797 --> 15:39.524
They just let Leslie
Van Houten out of the joint.

15:39.559 --> 15:41.941
Correct.

15:41.975 --> 15:43.943
And I hear she likes camping.

15:49.500 --> 15:50.000
♪

16:07.828 --> 16:11.004
Fred and Dave
do not travel light.

16:11.039 --> 16:13.041
♪

16:13.075 --> 16:15.284
Previously acquired stunt moose,

16:15.319 --> 16:17.873
the legs slow-roasted
over an open fire,

16:17.907 --> 16:21.463
the ribs of the same beast
braised on the coals,

16:21.497 --> 16:24.673
and natural gravy simmers away.

16:24.707 --> 16:27.158
A cured ham bought from
our generous friend

16:27.193 --> 16:29.540
Marc Tampica in Montreal.

16:29.574 --> 16:31.576
♪

16:31.611 --> 16:34.510
But first, cans.

16:34.545 --> 16:37.824
Oh, my good God.
Look at that thing.

16:37.858 --> 16:39.929
It's a jellied foie gras.

16:39.964 --> 16:41.862
Look at this thing.
Jesus.

16:41.897 --> 16:44.865
This is the proof
of our low self-esteem.

16:44.900 --> 16:48.593
A tureen of wild hare
drizzled with sauce.

16:48.628 --> 16:50.147
What... what... what...

16:50.181 --> 16:53.357
Another tureen of pheasant,
wild duck, and guinea hen

16:53.391 --> 16:56.015
loaded with pleasing hunks
of foie gras.

16:56.049 --> 16:57.050
Oh, look at that.

16:57.085 --> 16:59.052
A wild boar tureen.

16:59.087 --> 17:00.329
- Do you have boars here?
- No.

17:00.364 --> 17:02.745
- Hogzillas?
- No.

17:02.780 --> 17:03.781
That's another thing...

17:03.815 --> 17:05.058
"Hogzilla"?

17:05.093 --> 17:06.535
I think it would be
an amazing legacy

17:06.541 --> 17:09.061
for Joe Beef to introduce
a foreign species

17:09.097 --> 17:10.098
to Newfoundland.

17:10.132 --> 17:11.892
I think that's awesome.

17:11.926 --> 17:15.413
Like, that's the kind of shit
people don't do anymore.

17:15.448 --> 17:16.794
Mmm.

17:16.828 --> 17:18.415
Wow.

17:18.451 --> 17:21.247
So you're mixing canned
and fresh truffle.

17:21.281 --> 17:23.559
Yeah, because we can,

17:23.594 --> 17:26.079
the same reason
the dog eats his ass.

17:27.943 --> 17:29.772
'Cause he can.

17:35.502 --> 17:37.608
After a humiliation in the wild

17:37.642 --> 17:40.093
as severe as ours,
as sporting gentlemen,

17:40.128 --> 17:43.372
it is required
that we discharge our weapons.

17:43.407 --> 17:45.236
Yeah!
Repeatedly.

17:45.271 --> 17:48.136
In this case,
at nonliving things.

17:49.861 --> 17:51.691
All right, pull.

17:54.970 --> 17:56.109
Got a fish.

17:56.144 --> 17:57.766
Okay, pull.

18:00.769 --> 18:03.979
What are the symptoms
of lead poisoning?

18:04.013 --> 18:06.223
Uh, inability to hit a skeet?

18:06.257 --> 18:08.294
Pull.

18:08.328 --> 18:10.261
It's a bad place
for hippies to go camp

18:10.296 --> 18:11.469
on the other side.

18:11.504 --> 18:12.919
Yeah.

18:12.953 --> 18:15.404
Pull.

18:15.439 --> 18:16.233
Pull.

18:17.475 --> 18:19.926
Pull.

18:22.273 --> 18:25.897
Is that the stuff you learn
in West Virginistan?

18:32.904 --> 18:34.147
Our main course arrives

18:34.182 --> 18:37.875
as the temperature drops.

18:37.909 --> 18:39.601
Moose shoulder and ribs,

18:39.635 --> 18:41.603
neck braised in red wine,

18:41.637 --> 18:44.847
wild mushrooms,
and grilled Scotch lovage

18:44.882 --> 18:46.987
for the essential
vegetable component.

18:47.022 --> 18:50.646
And roast chestnuts, bacon,
and pearl onions.

18:50.681 --> 18:54.478
Whoa. Look at that.
It's gorgeous.

18:54.512 --> 18:56.335
We didn't shoot a moose,
but we're gonna taste a moose.

18:56.342 --> 18:57.998
That's good.

19:03.003 --> 19:04.212
Wow.

19:04.246 --> 19:06.283
Yeah, that's.

19:06.317 --> 19:09.251
- Who's that?
- Thank you.

19:14.187 --> 19:16.051
Wow, it's good.

19:16.085 --> 19:18.467
Moose meat, best meat.
Number one meat in the world.

19:18.502 --> 19:20.987
No better meat than the moose.
That's for sure.

19:21.021 --> 19:24.508
♪

19:24.542 --> 19:25.888
- Wow.
- Yeah.

19:25.923 --> 19:27.166
This is amazing.

19:27.200 --> 19:29.651
♪

19:29.685 --> 19:31.998
I think that it's a treat
and it's...

19:32.032 --> 19:35.381
I've said for years that
moose meat is the best meat,

19:35.415 --> 19:39.316
the champagne
of animal proteins.

19:39.350 --> 19:41.732
You're right.
It is something special.

19:41.766 --> 19:44.942
Don't even mind the rain
anymore.

19:46.357 --> 19:47.703
Look at that.
Like, what is that?

19:47.738 --> 19:49.429
It's amazing.
It's a gray jay.

19:49.464 --> 19:50.568
He'll just hop in your hand.

19:50.603 --> 19:52.052
- Would he?
- He might.

19:52.087 --> 19:54.365
Put something in your hand,
and he'll get it.

19:56.160 --> 19:58.507
Look, he's on the camera.

19:58.542 --> 20:00.958
I want... I really want
to do this.

20:00.992 --> 20:02.856
He's gone?
Oh, he's on...

20:02.891 --> 20:04.030
Oh, he's on Tony's head.

20:05.100 --> 20:06.688
Animals love me.

20:06.722 --> 20:08.207
I told you.

20:08.241 --> 20:11.865
I'm like St. Francis of Assisi.

20:11.900 --> 20:14.523
Oh, look, they really are
hitting the ham.

20:14.558 --> 20:16.698
Oh, this could get ugly
really quickly.

20:16.732 --> 20:18.555
Next thing you know, they're
pecking our eyeballs out

20:18.562 --> 20:20.322
and tunneling up our asses.

20:36.269 --> 20:37.546
63 feet.

20:37.581 --> 20:40.756
Okay.
We're ready to go.

20:42.413 --> 20:43.752
Thank you, sir.
What are we drinking?

20:43.759 --> 20:45.071
A little Benjamin Bridge

20:45.105 --> 20:46.831
out of Nova Scotia.

20:46.866 --> 20:49.178
- Cheers.
- Gentlemen, cheers.

20:49.213 --> 20:50.939
To the queen.

20:54.425 --> 20:56.289
No, I hate the aristocracy, man.

20:56.324 --> 20:57.808
They don't have long.

20:57.842 --> 21:00.189
Raymonds in St. John's
is probably

21:00.224 --> 21:03.572
the best-known, most celebrated
restaurant in Newfoundland.

21:03.607 --> 21:05.091
It's gotten the region

21:05.125 --> 21:06.955
national, even international
attention

21:06.989 --> 21:10.407
with its hyper-localized,
wildly creative menus.

21:10.441 --> 21:12.616
Wow, this is exciting.

21:12.650 --> 21:15.550
Whoa. Wow.

21:16.861 --> 21:18.829
Seafood tower.
Yes!

21:18.863 --> 21:24.006
Razor clams, snow crab,
mussels, capelin, whelk,

21:24.041 --> 21:25.284
and sea urchin.

21:25.318 --> 21:26.354
Oh, look at that.

21:26.388 --> 21:29.633
Little plump sacs of goodness.

21:31.566 --> 21:33.878
Oh, God, that's good.

21:33.913 --> 21:37.330
Boquerones, I'm very
excited about as well.

21:37.365 --> 21:39.159
Whelks is my game.

21:39.194 --> 21:41.300
- Really?
- Oh, love 'em.

21:41.334 --> 21:44.648
The boquerones
are quite remarkable.

21:47.202 --> 21:48.617
This is really good.

21:48.652 --> 21:50.343
I'm gonna pass the tuna around.

21:53.277 --> 21:55.175
I like the little berries.

21:55.210 --> 21:58.178
It's funny; there's no oysters
on this or clams, which is...

21:58.213 --> 21:59.973
- Right.
- Refreshing.

22:00.008 --> 22:02.010
I don't think
I've ever seen that.

22:02.044 --> 22:04.737
No.
It's only local.

22:13.539 --> 22:15.920
Here you go.

22:20.891 --> 22:22.996
Today we're just gonna do

22:23.031 --> 22:24.032
just a scallop crudo.

22:24.066 --> 22:25.654
Basically raw scallops

22:25.689 --> 22:28.381
just with a salt, fresh herbs,
and a few simple garnishes.

22:28.416 --> 22:29.417
It doesn't need much.

22:29.451 --> 22:30.445
It is what it is, you know?

22:30.452 --> 22:31.764
Speaks for itself.

22:31.798 --> 22:33.248
Ready?

22:33.282 --> 22:35.181
For me, the ocean,
the definition of the ocean,

22:35.215 --> 22:38.426
when I think of the ocean,
I think of New England,

22:38.460 --> 22:40.497
the northern part of France.

22:40.531 --> 22:44.742
You know, magnificent,
steel gray, intimidating.

22:46.986 --> 22:47.486
♪

22:51.473 --> 22:53.302
It's the coldest [...] water.

22:53.337 --> 22:55.304
Iceland?
Here?

22:55.339 --> 22:56.685
- Sterile.
- Northern Europe?

22:56.720 --> 22:58.411
- Northern Atlantic.
- Right.

22:58.446 --> 22:59.964
- It's where it's all about.
- Yeah.

22:59.999 --> 23:02.450
Or for me, it was always
where it's all about.

23:03.761 --> 23:06.799
There's no draggers, no nothing.

23:06.833 --> 23:08.732
You know, friends of mine
who gear up

23:08.766 --> 23:10.727
and who are crazy enough
to jump in the Atlantic Ocean

23:10.734 --> 23:12.252
and go to the bottom,

23:12.287 --> 23:15.221
they emerge with these baskets
of beautiful scallops.

23:15.255 --> 23:17.844
All right, let's get started.

23:23.194 --> 23:24.230
Look at them.

23:24.264 --> 23:25.258
The nerves are still in it.

23:25.265 --> 23:27.060
See it there?

23:27.095 --> 23:28.510
Fresh scallop.

23:38.865 --> 23:42.282
Just want to keep it
pretty simple, you know?

23:42.317 --> 23:43.732
They're delicious.

23:43.767 --> 23:45.907
You can't get
much fresher than that.

23:45.941 --> 23:47.874
No, I would say.

23:54.778 --> 23:56.676
I myself, I take it on myself

23:56.711 --> 23:58.989
to turn it into
nasturtium tacos.

23:59.023 --> 24:00.300
Tacos of scallop.

24:00.335 --> 24:01.474
I love nasturtiums.

24:01.509 --> 24:03.165
Wow.

24:03.200 --> 24:06.686
- We're eating Newfoundland.
- Yeah.

24:09.033 --> 24:11.519
We're so fortunate here
in Newfoundland and Labrador

24:11.553 --> 24:13.590
to be able to serve wild game...

24:13.624 --> 24:17.283
Moose, rabbits, partridge,
grouse.

24:17.317 --> 24:19.837
It's a really big part,
big staple

24:19.872 --> 24:21.494
of our menu, obviously.

24:21.529 --> 24:22.944
It's the reason why

24:22.978 --> 24:24.704
the restaurant's
pretty much open, you know?

24:24.739 --> 24:26.319
Nowhere else in the country
you can do that.

24:26.326 --> 24:27.673
Heart of caribou tartar

24:27.707 --> 24:29.640
with Adler and chanterelle.

24:29.675 --> 24:31.159
I'm enjoying this meal.

24:31.193 --> 24:32.229
Yeah, man, it's...

24:32.263 --> 24:33.368
Very, very, very much.

24:33.402 --> 24:34.611
This is really, really good.

24:34.645 --> 24:36.164
Jeremy Charles, in my opinion,

24:36.198 --> 24:39.685
honestly, I would say
easily top chef in Canada,

24:39.719 --> 24:41.203
most likely, you know?

24:41.238 --> 24:46.623
As a model of bravery,
determination, courage, pride.

24:46.657 --> 24:48.694
And not a false note.

24:48.728 --> 24:53.008
We've not had anything
that's not from this island.

24:54.182 --> 24:56.736
What we got here
is the cod sound.

24:56.771 --> 24:59.152
It's the swim bladder
of the codfish.

24:59.187 --> 25:01.154
Just goes right up the middle
of the fish.

25:01.189 --> 25:03.985
We've been toying around
with this for a long time.

25:04.019 --> 25:07.195
This is almost like
boot leather, you know?

25:07.229 --> 25:08.403
It's really, really tough.

25:08.437 --> 25:10.681
So we'll salt it overnight.

25:10.716 --> 25:14.098
Then we'll soak it,
and then we'll dehydrate it.

25:14.133 --> 25:16.238
And this is the part
of you're left with.

25:16.273 --> 25:19.897
It's almost like a chicharrón
type of texture, you know?

25:19.932 --> 25:21.416
But my grandmother,
she'd probably just

25:21.450 --> 25:23.107
render up pork fat scrunchions,

25:23.142 --> 25:25.903
and they just fry these off,
you know?

25:25.938 --> 25:31.012
So what we'll do then is,
we'll drop that in the oil.

25:31.046 --> 25:34.049
And it's gonna puff up,
become this beautiful chip.

25:41.988 --> 25:44.853
Charred whelk with [indistinct]

25:44.888 --> 25:47.097
And crispy cod sounds.

25:49.168 --> 25:53.586
What was this?
Sound, floating bladder.

25:53.621 --> 25:55.208
Bladder.
Yeah, I like that.

25:55.243 --> 25:56.451
Mmm, good.
Bladder.

25:56.485 --> 25:57.763
- It's what?
- Fried bladder.

25:57.797 --> 26:00.593
Smell it, though.
It's good.

26:00.628 --> 26:03.389
It's delicious.

26:05.805 --> 26:08.877
The onslaught of food continues.

26:08.912 --> 26:11.570
Cod fillet
with cod liver [indistinct],

26:11.604 --> 26:13.088
partridge profiteroles,

26:13.123 --> 26:15.470
and this, the classic
Newfoundland staple,

26:15.504 --> 26:18.749
Jiggs dinner,
reinvented into a pasta dish.

26:18.784 --> 26:20.993
It's beautiful.
Oh, it's good.

26:21.027 --> 26:22.097
Mmm.

26:22.132 --> 26:24.824
- It's spectacular.
- Yeah.

26:24.859 --> 26:26.239
I'll go so far as saying

26:26.274 --> 26:27.613
it's the best pasta
I've ever eaten.

26:27.620 --> 26:29.484
Wow.

26:29.518 --> 26:31.624
The pasta itself
is extraordinary.

26:31.659 --> 26:33.902
Even the detail
in this room is amazing.

26:33.937 --> 26:37.009
Even the carpets, if you notice.

26:39.287 --> 26:40.288
No!

26:40.322 --> 26:41.669
We have a pair for you.

26:41.703 --> 26:43.981
No way.

26:44.016 --> 26:47.433
That's super creepy.
I'm alarmed.

26:47.467 --> 26:48.698
As you step away
from the urinal,

26:48.710 --> 26:51.851
are you shaking the last
couple of drops...

26:51.886 --> 26:53.957
- Yes.
- On my face every time?

26:53.991 --> 26:56.511
Wow, I don't know what to say.

26:56.545 --> 26:58.547
I'm stunned.

27:01.412 --> 27:05.002
Last but not least,
it's chanterelle ice cream.

27:05.037 --> 27:07.211
- Oh, it's good.
- Mmm.

27:07.246 --> 27:08.627
Ooh.

27:08.661 --> 27:10.698
It tastes like
farmer's daughter.

27:10.732 --> 27:13.010
That musty funk, you know,
in the hayloft?

27:13.045 --> 27:15.047
That was spectacular
ice cream, though, for real.

27:15.081 --> 27:18.637
I'm, like... I'm mad at you for
not having made this already.

27:18.671 --> 27:20.121
No, no, no.

27:20.155 --> 27:22.295
You're the king
of soft-serve flavors,

27:22.330 --> 27:24.643
but you've not done
chanterelle ice cream?

27:24.677 --> 27:26.127
Fred, I'm kind of pissed.

27:26.161 --> 27:28.163
Tons of it.
You just never pay attention.

27:29.268 --> 27:30.649
It's kind of dirty

27:30.683 --> 27:32.133
in a good way.

27:32.167 --> 27:34.376
I mean, a really good way.

27:41.832 --> 27:42.332
♪

27:52.774 --> 27:55.708
I hope they don't find
that 8-ball.

27:55.743 --> 27:56.243
♪

27:59.850 --> 28:01.507
How long is the flight?

28:01.541 --> 28:02.888
Just about 45 minutes.

28:02.922 --> 28:04.199
45 minutes?

28:04.234 --> 28:05.891
That's enough to see, you know,

28:05.925 --> 28:07.656
all the good films
that Michael Bay ever made.

28:08.756 --> 28:10.896
I'm going to France.

28:10.930 --> 28:14.347
Not like Francophone Canada
but France.

28:14.382 --> 28:15.555
Really.

28:15.590 --> 28:17.074
A little bit of actual France

28:17.109 --> 28:19.559
sitting about 45 minutes
offshore.

28:19.594 --> 28:21.907
The islands
of Saint Pierre and Miquelon,

28:21.941 --> 28:25.738
France's last foothold
in North America.

28:25.773 --> 28:28.223
French cars, French food,

28:28.258 --> 28:31.917
pay in Euros,
and French attitude.

28:31.951 --> 28:35.023
♪

28:38.233 --> 28:38.733
♪

28:51.419 --> 28:55.388
We have a French way of life
here, really.

28:55.423 --> 28:58.806
We eat French.
I think we think French also.

28:58.840 --> 29:00.566
Almost.

29:00.600 --> 29:03.465
Our hosts on this otherwise
male-centric brocation

29:03.500 --> 29:05.605
are Maite and her friend Hilary.

29:05.640 --> 29:07.746
People around here
don't eat out much.

29:07.780 --> 29:11.473
Instead, most cook at home,
often with friends.

29:11.508 --> 29:13.613
This is sea urchin paté.

29:13.648 --> 29:15.098
- Yes!
- What?

29:15.132 --> 29:19.067
Paté d'oursin,
a sea urchin paté.

29:19.102 --> 29:20.966
Plump sacs of roe
fresh off the beach

29:21.000 --> 29:22.588
formed into a loaf

29:22.622 --> 29:25.073
and cooked with bread, garlic,
and onions.

29:25.108 --> 29:26.903
And utterly delicious.

29:26.937 --> 29:30.423
- Look at that.
- This is a try.

29:30.458 --> 29:32.287
Wow, it's pretty.

29:32.322 --> 29:34.600
Look at that.

29:34.634 --> 29:36.982
Wow, it's sensational.

29:37.016 --> 29:39.122
- You like it?
- Mmm, fantastic.

29:39.156 --> 29:41.262
- Good.
- Wow, that's good.

29:41.296 --> 29:43.920
You know, this is a kind
of dish for real we should do.

29:43.954 --> 29:45.162
That's a very good idea.

29:45.197 --> 29:46.854
Urchins,
transform it all at once

29:46.888 --> 29:48.441
when it's at the peak
of freshness,

29:48.476 --> 29:50.616
make a solid paté,
and serve it slice by slice

29:50.650 --> 29:52.031
like foie gras, you know?

29:52.066 --> 29:54.102
My mind's already racing.
Urchin sausages.

29:54.137 --> 29:56.380
Steal this recipe, dude.
This is good.

29:56.415 --> 29:58.382
Well, we'll have to call it
Paté Maite.

29:58.417 --> 30:02.041
Well, my goodness.
What an honor.

30:02.076 --> 30:05.113
I don't have copyrights on that,
because it's local.

30:05.148 --> 30:07.288
- Classic.
- Really traditional food here.

30:07.322 --> 30:10.532
It is that you've had this
all your life?

30:10.567 --> 30:12.189
- Yes.
- Wow.

30:15.434 --> 30:15.934
♪

30:20.059 --> 30:22.648
Stuffed squid over rice.

30:22.682 --> 30:24.684
♪

30:24.719 --> 30:27.687
Oh!
This is family style.

30:27.722 --> 30:29.758
- Nice!
- Wowee.

30:29.793 --> 30:31.553
Wow, look at that.

30:31.588 --> 30:35.557
♪

30:35.592 --> 30:37.525
Wow.
Thank you.

30:37.559 --> 30:41.011
♪

30:41.046 --> 30:43.186
Mmm.
Do you want some rice with it?

30:43.220 --> 30:44.256
Wow.

30:44.290 --> 30:47.017
You know, traditional
and family meal.

30:47.052 --> 30:49.502
Yeah.
You're an amazing cook.

30:49.537 --> 30:51.504
- Thank you.
- This is really great.

30:51.539 --> 30:53.361
Maybe you're gonna have to
open a small, little restaurant.

30:53.368 --> 30:54.853
Did you ever think of that?

30:54.887 --> 30:57.579
Well, I'm planning
to open a pastry shop.

30:57.614 --> 30:58.857
- Really?
- Yeah.

30:58.891 --> 31:00.720
You bake as well?

31:00.755 --> 31:03.516
♪

31:03.551 --> 31:07.003
Braised halibut...
Simple and perfect.

31:07.037 --> 31:10.351
- Halibut.
- Wow, look at that.

31:10.385 --> 31:11.524
♪

31:11.559 --> 31:13.872
Are these are potatoes
from here?

31:13.906 --> 31:15.011
From France.

31:16.633 --> 31:18.359
Oh, no.
We would like to.

31:18.393 --> 31:20.464
Le Charlotte?
La belle de Fontenay?

31:20.499 --> 31:23.433
Your knowledge of tubers
is dazzling.

31:23.467 --> 31:26.056
Fred has an incredible amount
of pedantic knowledge

31:26.091 --> 31:28.300
about several subjects.

31:28.334 --> 31:30.889
Oh, wow.
This is great.

31:30.923 --> 31:34.478
♪

31:37.516 --> 31:38.016
♪

31:49.424 --> 31:52.565
At this point, there's only
one thing missing.

31:52.600 --> 31:54.257
Oh, wow.
Wow!

31:54.291 --> 31:57.225
- No way.
- Local cheese.

31:57.260 --> 31:59.089
Glorious cheese.

31:59.124 --> 32:00.919
And this is...

32:00.953 --> 32:03.059
This is a tart, creme de mon.

32:03.093 --> 32:05.061
- With urchins.
- No.

32:05.095 --> 32:09.065
With baked apples
and blackberries from here.

32:09.099 --> 32:10.998
Fantastic.

32:11.032 --> 32:12.516
♪

32:12.551 --> 32:14.311
You have to open
a little [inaudible]

32:14.346 --> 32:15.864
Or something like that.

32:15.899 --> 32:17.970
You have so much talent
in cooking and sourcing

32:18.005 --> 32:19.282
and talking about it.

32:19.316 --> 32:20.697
Don't stick to the pastry shop.

32:20.731 --> 32:22.181
That's my gut feeling.

32:22.216 --> 32:24.804
I want to talk to you
about financials as well.

32:24.839 --> 32:28.084
I want to talk to you about how,
when you say "tea shop,"

32:28.118 --> 32:29.154
there's no money in it.

32:29.188 --> 32:30.189
You have to sell wine.

32:30.224 --> 32:31.984
Make a small wine bar.

32:32.019 --> 32:34.676
A wine bar is a license
to print money.

32:34.711 --> 32:36.955
Wow.
Thank you, guys.

32:36.989 --> 32:38.715
Thank you so much.

32:38.749 --> 32:41.028
I'm so happy with this cheese.

32:41.062 --> 32:43.720
The meal in general,
all of it was fantastic.

32:43.754 --> 32:44.997
I'm so happy.

32:45.032 --> 32:47.103
This is what I needed.

32:47.137 --> 32:48.166
This is really a throwback.

32:48.173 --> 32:49.519
This is the sort of meal

32:49.553 --> 32:51.031
you have a hard time finding
in France now.

32:51.038 --> 32:52.315
- Yeah.
- Correct me if I'm wrong.

32:52.349 --> 32:53.799
You really have a hard time

32:53.833 --> 32:58.700
finding a true, proud
French regional meal.

32:58.735 --> 33:01.082
It's incredibly difficult.

33:09.918 --> 33:12.991
I am, above all things,
a man of the people,

33:13.025 --> 33:14.647
a regular Joe,

33:14.682 --> 33:17.409
a man as moved by a simple
slab of Mom's meatloaf

33:17.443 --> 33:19.825
as I am of lark's tongues
in aspic

33:19.859 --> 33:21.482
studded with truffles

33:21.516 --> 33:23.863
and moistened with the tears
of baby unicorn.

33:23.898 --> 33:26.763
Big R's provides the local
version of comfort food

33:26.797 --> 33:29.697
that all of us...
Chefs and regulars...

33:29.731 --> 33:31.043
Want and need.

33:31.078 --> 33:32.665
Now, correct me if I'm wrong.

33:32.700 --> 33:36.566
The indigenous specialties
would be the Jiggs dinner.

33:36.600 --> 33:37.877
Yeah.

33:37.912 --> 33:41.053
And we got to get
the Funyuns, the bunions.

33:41.088 --> 33:42.185
The scrunchions.
Scrunchions?

33:42.192 --> 33:43.745
The truncheons, the...

33:43.780 --> 33:45.057
You think they can whip up

33:45.092 --> 33:48.336
some beets and goat cheese
for me?

33:51.581 --> 33:52.081
♪

33:56.241 --> 33:57.725
Fried baloney.

33:57.759 --> 34:01.211
And don't sneer.
It's awesome.

34:01.246 --> 34:02.971
♪

34:03.006 --> 34:05.802
And you got to have
some fried clam strips...

34:05.836 --> 34:06.941
For Dave, anyway.

34:06.975 --> 34:09.702
Liver and onions for Fred.

34:09.737 --> 34:10.462
♪

34:10.496 --> 34:12.878
Pan-fried cods tongues.

34:12.911 --> 34:13.411
♪

34:16.951 --> 34:19.436
They call it a Jiggs dinner,

34:19.471 --> 34:23.716
perhaps the ultimate
Newfoundland classic,

34:23.751 --> 34:26.719
like a pot-au-feu or
a New England boiled dinner...

34:26.754 --> 34:31.206
Basically boiled salt beef,
cabbage, turnips, potatoes,

34:31.241 --> 34:34.072
and peas pudding
topped with gravy...

34:34.106 --> 34:36.212
Preferably, lots of gravy.

34:36.246 --> 34:37.972
♪

34:38.005 --> 34:40.733
Oh, this is magnificent.

34:40.768 --> 34:43.114
This is something you'd have
at your grandmother's house.

34:43.150 --> 34:45.221
Really?
It's basically pot-au-feu.

34:45.255 --> 34:46.601
It's beautiful.

34:46.636 --> 34:49.016
And one gravies this
without apologies.

34:49.052 --> 34:50.916
Yeah, no apologies.

34:53.367 --> 34:57.302
♪

34:57.336 --> 34:59.994
Oh, that's good.
Yeah.

35:00.028 --> 35:01.271
I love this gravy.

35:01.306 --> 35:03.101
Give the boys the recipe

35:03.135 --> 35:04.930
for the Joe Beef Swiss chard.

35:04.964 --> 35:06.173
Oh, it's amazing.

35:06.207 --> 35:08.106
A lot of Swiss chard
in the restaurant.

35:08.140 --> 35:09.348
And the gardens as well.

35:09.383 --> 35:10.687
And for years
and years and years,

35:10.694 --> 35:12.040
we used to serve it
to customers,

35:12.075 --> 35:13.111
and they never liked it.

35:13.145 --> 35:14.629
Wow.

35:14.664 --> 35:18.150
So what we started doing is,
we split the stems

35:18.185 --> 35:19.289
from the greens.

35:19.324 --> 35:20.842
We'll take the stems.

35:20.877 --> 35:22.354
We'll blanch them, like,
in the Presto oven.

35:22.361 --> 35:24.950
Then we'll juice them.

35:24.984 --> 35:26.434
Mmm!
I'm happy.

35:26.469 --> 35:28.712
We'll take the juice, reduce it.

35:28.747 --> 35:31.129
Then we'll char lightly
the leaves.

35:31.163 --> 35:32.440
- Clam strip.
- Thank you kindly.

35:32.475 --> 35:34.028
We'll chop them, season it,

35:34.062 --> 35:36.789
and we'll combine both
with a bit of butter.

35:36.824 --> 35:38.715
Swap you a little bit of
baloney for a clam strip.

35:38.722 --> 35:40.483
You okay with that?
I'm going in.

35:40.517 --> 35:41.794
Sometimes we put the peppers

35:41.829 --> 35:43.348
and smoke in the smoker.

35:43.382 --> 35:44.487
All right.
Cheers.

35:44.521 --> 35:45.798
We'll bake it in the oven

35:45.833 --> 35:47.317
with parmesan cheese
and breadcrumb,

35:47.352 --> 35:49.216
and then we'll toss it
in the garbage.

35:49.250 --> 35:51.390
Immediately.

35:51.425 --> 35:55.153
♪

35:58.190 --> 35:59.743
You know what I like to do

35:59.778 --> 36:02.643
on a sausage-fest-themed show
like this one?

36:02.677 --> 36:05.991
I like to get liquored up
and throw axes at a target,

36:06.025 --> 36:07.525
hoping, of course,
they don't bounce off

36:07.544 --> 36:09.167
and sink into my groin

36:09.201 --> 36:10.685
or somebody else's groin.

36:10.720 --> 36:12.308
I hate when that happens.

36:12.342 --> 36:13.550
Have you done this before?

36:13.585 --> 36:15.173
I've thrown axes.
I throw axes.

36:15.207 --> 36:16.201
Yeah, I had a throwing ax board

36:16.208 --> 36:17.520
in the back of Joe Beef

36:17.554 --> 36:19.211
until I realized
it wasn't really safe.

36:19.246 --> 36:21.386
♪

36:21.420 --> 36:23.181
Try not to cut your own ear off?

36:23.215 --> 36:25.424
You want to draw back
nice and slow over your head.

36:25.459 --> 36:27.495
Lean right in.
When your arm is straight out

36:27.530 --> 36:29.221
and it's parallel
with the ground...

36:29.256 --> 36:31.085
- That's when you release.
- That's it.

36:31.119 --> 36:33.398
Is there a William Tell
kind of story in Newfoundland

36:33.432 --> 36:34.502
with a cod over the head

36:34.537 --> 36:36.849
and a father that threw the ax?

36:36.884 --> 36:38.920
Not yet.
Not yet.

36:38.955 --> 36:40.232
Do it proud.

36:41.958 --> 36:43.546
Go, Fred.

36:46.065 --> 36:47.964
Watch your head, there.

36:50.311 --> 36:53.418
All right, so far,
we kind of suck.

36:55.972 --> 36:58.319
This is not encouraging.

37:06.741 --> 37:09.365
Try the double hand, yeah.

37:09.399 --> 37:11.401
Oh, that was close.

37:15.750 --> 37:17.373
You know what I'm gonna do?

37:17.407 --> 37:18.719
I'm gonna put my ax to good use

37:18.753 --> 37:20.962
and cut a little bit
of that Muenster cheese.

37:20.997 --> 37:23.931
Now you're talking.

37:23.965 --> 37:26.727
Let's have a little pork
and stinky cheese.

37:26.761 --> 37:29.833
We'll become Thor,
the thunder god.

37:29.868 --> 37:31.283
Mmm.

37:31.318 --> 37:32.657
Oh, here we go.
I'm gonna try again.

37:32.664 --> 37:35.322
I will get this right.

37:36.599 --> 37:38.099
We're going back to drinking
after this;

37:38.117 --> 37:39.567
I can tell you right now.

37:39.602 --> 37:42.605
Something I excel at.

37:42.639 --> 37:44.814
- Oh, yes.
- Oh!

37:44.848 --> 37:46.402
Wow.

37:46.436 --> 37:49.336
Now I'm making
my David tattoo even bigger.

37:50.613 --> 37:51.924
I'm gonna concentrate.

37:51.959 --> 37:53.436
I'm gonna think of someone
I really, really,

37:53.443 --> 37:55.790
really, really, really hate.

37:56.619 --> 37:59.346
- Yes!
- Oh!

38:01.002 --> 38:03.626
Oh, [...].

38:07.526 --> 38:09.494
Oh, [...] you.

38:09.528 --> 38:11.323
You look like a serial killer.

38:11.358 --> 38:12.980
Well, he killed a two-pack.

38:20.712 --> 38:22.438
Hear ye, hear ye, hear ye!

38:22.472 --> 38:23.956
Yeah!

38:23.991 --> 38:26.614
Let's bring the Royal Order
of Screeches to order.

38:30.825 --> 38:33.241
One final bit of business
remains

38:33.276 --> 38:35.347
in this enchanted land
called Newfoundland:

38:35.382 --> 38:39.178
an ancient and solemn ritual
reserved for newcomers,

38:39.213 --> 38:41.457
an official welcome,
an initiation,

38:41.491 --> 38:44.183
a way of saying,
"You are welcome.

38:44.218 --> 38:47.152
You are maybe now one of us."

38:47.186 --> 38:49.465
Oh, there's fire involved.

38:49.499 --> 38:51.743
It's always fun
when there's fire involved.

38:51.777 --> 38:53.365
I feel much better about this.

38:55.781 --> 38:58.543
Today I will be screeched in.

38:58.577 --> 39:00.234
I do need you to take
a small piece

39:00.268 --> 39:01.511
of Newfoundland steak.

39:01.546 --> 39:03.341
- Is it organic?
- Yes, of course, yes.

39:04.721 --> 39:06.654
Do not worry about it
if you're vegetarian;

39:06.689 --> 39:08.207
there's not much meat in it.

39:08.242 --> 39:09.381
Thank you kindly.

39:09.416 --> 39:11.901
And David and Tony.

39:11.935 --> 39:15.870
And David.

39:15.905 --> 39:18.873
- Thank you very much.
- You're welcome.

39:24.603 --> 39:26.260
♪

39:26.294 --> 39:31.023
In 1497, there was a man
by the name of John Cabot.

39:31.058 --> 39:33.405
John Cabot sailed the Atlantic
on his boat, the "Matthew,"

39:33.440 --> 39:34.434
all the way
from Bristol, England,

39:34.441 --> 39:35.890
to Bonavista Bay.

39:35.925 --> 39:38.237
And when he arrived,
he saw lots of activity

39:38.272 --> 39:39.446
in our water.

39:39.480 --> 39:41.033
Now, he didn't know
what was going on,

39:41.068 --> 39:43.063
but he dropped his bucket down
to fill it up with water,

39:43.070 --> 39:44.796
and when it came up
to the top of the boat,

39:44.830 --> 39:47.523
it was filled right to the rim
with codfish.

39:47.557 --> 39:48.869
Now, word got out fast

39:48.903 --> 39:50.595
how plentiful the fish were
in our waters

39:50.629 --> 39:52.631
that they traveled from all over
to settled here

39:52.666 --> 39:54.005
and to catch the fish,
sell the fish,

39:54.012 --> 39:56.221
trade the fish
all around the world

39:56.255 --> 39:57.774
as a means of survival.

39:57.809 --> 40:00.398
And one place in particular
that we traded with

40:00.432 --> 40:01.571
was with Jamaica,

40:01.606 --> 40:04.091
'cause in Jamaica,
they make rum,

40:04.125 --> 40:06.058
and we loved rum.

40:07.197 --> 40:08.440
We loved it so much

40:08.475 --> 40:09.641
that we would actually get
on that wharf,

40:09.648 --> 40:11.167
and we'd kiss the fish good-bye,

40:11.201 --> 40:13.756
knowing that it was coming back
to us in the way of rum.

40:13.790 --> 40:16.793
So in keeping with that time
and honored tradition,

40:16.828 --> 40:19.762
I do have a little buddy
for you to meet.

40:21.211 --> 40:22.730
It's a Gremlin.

40:22.765 --> 40:27.079
This is a real Newfoundland
codfish.

40:27.114 --> 40:28.764
Given the chance, this fish
could have grown up

40:28.771 --> 40:30.911
to the height of 6 feet tall

40:30.945 --> 40:32.809
and weighed as much
as 130 pounds.

40:32.844 --> 40:34.604
This fish won't grow
any more than this,

40:34.639 --> 40:36.192
because it's dead.

40:38.332 --> 40:39.954
I do need you all to pucker up

40:39.989 --> 40:41.818
and give this fish
a little kiss.

40:41.853 --> 40:43.337
Excellent.
Fred, there we go.

40:43.371 --> 40:44.580
On the lips?

40:44.614 --> 40:45.960
You're best
to go first and last.

40:45.995 --> 40:48.169
And by Jesus, keep
that tongue in your mouth.

40:49.343 --> 40:50.965
Did you name your fish Valtrex?

40:51.000 --> 40:52.208
I will now.

40:52.242 --> 40:54.106
You were just in a strip club,
though, right?

40:54.141 --> 40:55.176
Were you... were you...

40:56.315 --> 40:57.627
Where did you put that mouth?

40:57.662 --> 40:59.940
Tony, you can't catch it twice.

41:04.669 --> 41:05.670
Oh, here, me darling.

41:05.704 --> 41:07.361
Oh, my God, Vince.

41:07.395 --> 41:08.776
Come on, love.
Lick up.

41:08.811 --> 41:11.020
This is like an aphrodisiac
for you two.

41:11.054 --> 41:12.608
Okay!

41:12.642 --> 41:14.851
And we can't have a drink
without having a toast,

41:14.886 --> 41:16.784
so please wait till
everybody gets their shot,

41:16.819 --> 41:18.372
and we'll do it together.

41:18.406 --> 41:19.615
Okay.

41:19.649 --> 41:22.134
So here's to health
and your company

41:22.169 --> 41:23.619
and one for the lasses.

41:23.653 --> 41:25.793
Let's drink and be merry
all out of our glasses.

41:25.828 --> 41:28.002
Let's drink and be merry,
bad thoughts to refrain,

41:28.037 --> 41:30.384
for we may or may not
ever all be here again.

41:30.418 --> 41:31.534
Up to the lips.
Over the gums.

41:31.558 --> 41:33.145
Look out, gullet.
Here she comes.

41:33.180 --> 41:36.148
Flush her back.

41:38.012 --> 41:42.396
Okay, now I now declare you all
honorary Newfoundlanders.

41:42.430 --> 41:43.811
Awesome.
There we go.

